00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:06.384
that you've researched, your own
experience, whether it drives

00:26:06.384 --> 00:26:07.800
fight-or-flight,
whether it drives

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:11.430
the unpleasant meeting that
we're having, it's something we

00:26:11.430 --> 00:26:11.930
let go.

00:26:11.930 --> 00:26:15.432
So what are your few tips to
squeeze into an extra half

00:26:15.432 --> 00:26:17.890
hour or an hour that will really
then make that difference?

00:26:17.890 --> 00:26:19.598
And I think maybe
share with the audience

00:26:19.598 --> 00:26:21.682
some of those kind of
findings that have come out.

00:26:21.682 --> 00:26:23.306
CAROLINE WEBB: We
all know on one level

00:26:23.306 --> 00:26:26.340
that the way we treat our body
affects the way our mind works.

00:26:26.340 --> 00:26:28.070
We know that when
we're under-slept,

00:26:28.070 --> 00:26:32.560
we become somehow less
witty and charming.

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:35.740
But we often behave as if
the connection isn't direct.

00:26:35.740 --> 00:26:38.880
We might accept that there's
a long-term connection.

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:41.700
But actually, the research
is really compelling.

00:26:41.700 --> 00:26:44.210
It says that the way
that you treat your body

00:26:44.210 --> 00:26:47.840
has an immediate effect
on your mental state.

00:26:47.840 --> 00:26:51.911
So the research on
exercise is fantastically

00:26:51.911 --> 00:26:53.410
encouraging for
someone like me, who

00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:55.220
does not like going to the gym.

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:57.580
I did a lot of sport when
I was younger as a kid.

00:26:57.580 --> 00:27:01.610
And then it's hard to fit
team sports into adult life.

00:27:01.610 --> 00:27:04.460
And so I always struggled
with getting enough exercise

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:06.180
into my day.

00:27:06.180 --> 00:27:08.980
I was personally very
encouraged by the research,

00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:11.770
which says in terms
of the benefits

00:27:11.770 --> 00:27:17.250
to your cognitive state,
doing more exercise boosts

00:27:17.250 --> 00:27:18.740
your emotional resilience.

00:27:18.740 --> 00:27:21.190
And it makes you
sharper and more focused

00:27:21.190 --> 00:27:25.100
and more analytically
smart-- immediately.

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:25.820
Goodness.

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:26.760
OK.

00:27:26.760 --> 00:27:29.800
You can get that after 20
minutes of moderate exercise.

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:32.310
I thought, OK, 20 minutes
moderate exercise.

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:33.890
That's a brisk walk.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:35.290
I can do that.

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:37.330
I started walking a lot more.

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:41.166
And I was even more encouraged
with more research that's

00:27:41.166 --> 00:27:42.790
been coming out in
the last year or two

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:45.400
which suggests that it's
not even just 20 minutes.

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:48.980
You can break it down into
chunks of 5 or 10 minutes.

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:52.420
There was one study that I
read that said, obviously,

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:54.300
more exercise might
be better than some,

00:27:54.300 --> 00:27:56.070
but some is better than none.

00:27:56.070 --> 00:27:57.330
And I took that to heart.

00:27:57.330 --> 00:27:58.900
So I walk a lot more.

00:27:58.900 --> 00:28:00.720
I seize every opportunity.

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:05.300
So we know that on one
level, that's a good thing.

00:28:05.300 --> 00:28:08.440
But actually, just to
know that it's immediately

00:28:08.440 --> 00:28:11.050
going to improve your
mood and your focus,

00:28:11.050 --> 00:28:13.400
that helps you put the time in.

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:17.405
And then with sleep,
yeah, it's interesting.

00:28:17.405 --> 00:28:20.970
Actually, I spoke at Google in
London a couple of weeks ago.

00:28:20.970 --> 00:28:23.030
And someone came
up to me afterwards

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:26.310
and said, if there's
one thing out of all

00:28:26.310 --> 00:28:28.430
of this physical stuff
that you're talking about

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:30.750
that I should be looking
after, what is it?

00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:33.860
And I said, well, it is sleep.

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:37.382
There's definitely
very clear research.

00:28:37.382 --> 00:28:39.840
You've probably heard about
this, that going short of sleep

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:42.960
is equivalent to
having a few drinks.

00:28:42.960 --> 00:28:47.080
And you wouldn't say that
someone at work who was short

00:28:47.080 --> 00:28:51.790
of sleep was an excellent
worker if they were drunk.

00:28:51.790 --> 00:28:55.226
But we have a slightly macho
approach to saying, you know,

00:28:55.226 --> 00:28:56.850
yeah, I only got four
hours last night.

00:28:56.850 --> 00:28:58.510
I'm working really hard.

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:01.660
The truth is that-- again,
all the evidence suggests--

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:05.190
that you have less
memory of what you did

00:29:05.190 --> 00:29:06.980
and you learn less
from what you're

00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:09.830
doing if you go short on sleep.

00:29:09.830 --> 00:29:11.550
So all of that, yes.

00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:13.270
So what do you then do?

00:29:13.270 --> 00:29:17.950
I think some of it is just
about an attitude and a mindset

00:29:17.950 --> 00:29:20.490
and not seeing
sleep as a luxury,

00:29:20.490 --> 00:29:22.530
not seeing sleep as
downtime, but seeing it

00:29:22.530 --> 00:29:24.930
as essential up-time.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:28.690
It's when your brain is doing
encoding and consolidation.

00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:31.320
And that subtle
shift into saying

00:29:31.320 --> 00:29:34.040
that this is actually going to
make me smarter when I wake up

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:37.400
tomorrow morning, I think
that's been very helpful for me.

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:42.310
That, and recognizing
that when you

00:29:42.310 --> 00:29:46.060
have a lot of light around
you-- and particularly lights

00:29:46.060 --> 00:29:50.320
from your devices-- it's going
to delay your sleep cycle.

00:29:50.320 --> 00:29:51.930
So there's research
at Harvard that's

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:54.060
more recent than some
of the sleep research

00:29:54.060 --> 00:29:58.617
saying that we push our
rhythms back by half an hour

00:29:58.617 --> 00:30:00.950
for every half an hour that
we're sitting with our phone

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:01.794
late at night.

00:30:01.794 --> 00:30:03.460
So there's something
about sleep hygiene

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:06.490
and just making sure that your
room is actually dark enough.

00:30:06.490 --> 00:30:08.228
And that really helps, too.

00:30:08.228 --> 00:30:09.196
ANANT SHUKLA: Yeah.

00:30:09.196 --> 00:30:11.850
In another chapter, I
think you mentioned--

00:30:11.850 --> 00:30:14.330
the whole chapter is about
managing relationships.

00:30:14.330 --> 00:30:17.840
And there are a few pages that
have common defensive mode

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:20.540
triggers that you might
elicit in a person you're

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:21.630
engaging with.

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:23.662
So can you touch upon
a little bit in some

00:30:23.662 --> 00:30:25.870
of these tense situations
where you don't necessarily

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:28.270
have the time to maybe
diagnose the situation

00:30:28.270 --> 00:30:31.580
or identify the
telltale sign-- how

00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:33.420
would you react accordingly?

00:30:33.420 --> 00:30:35.580
How can we, again,
implement those types

00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:37.340
of things on a quick notice?

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:39.480
And maybe even outline
for the audience

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:41.940
what those common defensive
triggers might be.

00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:43.815
CAROLINE WEBB: So what
Anant is talking about

00:30:43.815 --> 00:30:46.840
is that you know when someone
is behaving dysfunctionally.

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:50.040
And you've got this
split-second decision

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:52.930
where you can kind of
declare that they're a jerk,

00:30:52.930 --> 00:30:55.610
or you can decide that there
might be something going on

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:56.150
with them.

00:30:56.150 --> 00:30:58.120
And there's something
in psychology

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:00.380
which is called the
fundamental attribution error.

00:31:00.380 --> 00:31:02.744
And the way it works
is that if we show up

00:31:02.744 --> 00:31:04.160
and we're a bit
cranky at work, we

00:31:04.160 --> 00:31:06.250
know it's because we
didn't get enough sleep.

00:31:06.250 --> 00:31:09.260
But if someone else
is cranky, then we

00:31:09.260 --> 00:31:12.970
have a tendency to decide that
they're a terrible person.

00:31:12.970 --> 00:31:14.320
Because why?

00:31:14.320 --> 00:31:16.660
Because your brain is always
trying to take shortcuts.

00:31:16.660 --> 00:31:20.310
And it's a lot simpler to just
declare that this person is not

00:31:20.310 --> 00:31:22.705
that nice, versus
thinking about, well,

00:31:22.705 --> 00:31:24.420
what could be
going on with them?

00:31:24.420 --> 00:31:28.500
It's just simpler to just
badge them in a certain way.

00:31:28.500 --> 00:31:31.020
So one of the things
that you can do

00:31:31.020 --> 00:31:34.880
is just get yourself familiar
with the common triggers that

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:36.910
might be causing--
apart from lack

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:39.640
of sleep-- dysfunctional
behavior that might be putting

00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:40.840
someone into defensive mode.

00:31:40.840 --> 00:31:44.870
So there are individual ones,
like competence, autonomy,

00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:45.610
and security.

00:31:45.610 --> 00:31:48.320
Anything that undermines
someone's sense of competence,

00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:50.656
their autonomy, their
sense of security

00:31:50.656 --> 00:31:52.030
will put them into
defensive mode

00:31:52.030 --> 00:31:54.620
and make them behave badly.

00:31:54.620 --> 00:32:00.170
Then there are social needs,
like belonging and fairness

00:32:00.170 --> 00:32:00.810
and respect.

00:32:00.810 --> 00:32:04.130
And as soon as any of
those are violated at all,

00:32:04.130 --> 00:32:07.719
then you have a situation where,
again, that defensive mode

00:32:07.719 --> 00:32:08.760
is going to be triggered.

00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:10.640
So it helps to just
know the territory

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:12.590
and just to get into
the habit of saying,

00:32:12.590 --> 00:32:15.780
OK, this is probably
not a psychopath.

00:32:15.780 --> 00:32:17.900
This is probably--
just statistically,

00:32:17.900 --> 00:32:20.100
it's unlikely that
they're a psychopath.

00:32:20.100 --> 00:32:21.930
They're probably what
I call a good person

00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:23.460
in bad circumstances.

00:32:23.460 --> 00:32:24.950
What are the circumstances?

00:32:24.950 --> 00:32:28.402
You tell yourself a few
stories around those themes.

00:32:28.402 --> 00:32:30.110
Or it could be something
even more basic,

00:32:30.110 --> 00:32:31.784
like their cat died, right?

00:32:31.784 --> 00:32:32.950
That's not even on the list.

00:32:32.950 --> 00:32:35.480
That's just something
that makes you sad.

00:32:35.480 --> 00:32:38.880
So just stopping and
giving yourself that pause

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:40.830
and saying, what could
be going on with them,

00:32:40.830 --> 00:32:43.200
changes your demeanor
towards them,

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:45.770
which de-escalates
the situation.

00:32:45.770 --> 00:32:49.070
Because you are not then putting
them further on the defensive.

00:32:49.070 --> 00:32:50.754
And that is a great first step.

00:32:50.754 --> 00:32:52.670
And then there's a whole
bunch of other things

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:56.040
that you can do, like showing
appreciation-- fantastic silver

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:56.750
bullet.

00:32:56.750 --> 00:33:02.120
It hits competence,
security, belonging.

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:05.250
It makes for a quick way of
getting the other person out

00:33:05.250 --> 00:33:06.354
of defensive mode.

