00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:30.040
A lot of people that
I've met, I feel,

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:33.130
want to believe that they have
some special ability to just--

00:33:33.130 --> 00:33:37.174
they can juggle whatever
and check their email.

00:33:37.174 --> 00:33:39.590
And I'm just wondering if the
research that you saw really

00:33:39.590 --> 00:33:43.540
showed a gradient from
what people can handle

00:33:43.540 --> 00:33:46.304
and different people's
abilities, versus-- you're

00:33:46.304 --> 00:33:47.720
probably the best
person qualified

00:33:47.720 --> 00:33:49.050
to answer this question.

00:33:49.050 --> 00:33:50.200
So I might as well ask you.

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:51.250
CAROLINE WEBB: Thank you
very much for asking.

00:33:51.250 --> 00:33:51.749
Yeah.

00:33:51.749 --> 00:33:56.685
So one of the reasons that we
tend to think we can multitask

00:33:56.685 --> 00:34:00.130
is that there are certain things
we can multitask with, right?

00:34:00.130 --> 00:34:03.930
So if it's an automatic
task, the automatic system

00:34:03.930 --> 00:34:07.000
in our brain generally can do
multiple things in parallel.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:12.270
So that's why you can find your
way to work without necessarily

00:34:12.270 --> 00:34:13.790
concentrating on
where you're going

00:34:13.790 --> 00:34:15.206
while you're doing
something else,

00:34:15.206 --> 00:34:16.590
maybe checking your messages.

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:20.540
It's why when you're
driving, it might be possible

00:34:20.540 --> 00:34:23.310
for you to have a
conversation with someone.

00:34:23.310 --> 00:34:27.130
But the moment that anything
changes in the situation--

00:34:27.130 --> 00:34:29.449
perhaps you're driving
along and a car pulls out--

00:34:29.449 --> 00:34:33.340
and it requires conscious
attention from you,

00:34:33.340 --> 00:34:35.368
then you're back in
the mode of only being

00:34:35.368 --> 00:34:36.659
able to do one thing at a time.

00:34:36.659 --> 00:34:40.880
And that's why so many crashes
happen when people are talking.

00:34:40.880 --> 00:34:43.690
Because it feels as if
it's possible to do things

00:34:43.690 --> 00:34:44.190
in parallel.

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:47.256
And then something changes,
requires conscious attention.

00:34:47.256 --> 00:34:48.880
So I think that's
one of the reasons we

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:52.239
tend to believe that we
can with conscious tasks,

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:54.650
as well as with
unconscious tasks.

00:34:54.650 --> 00:34:56.436
But there's really
interesting research

00:34:56.436 --> 00:34:57.810
out there showing
that people who

00:34:57.810 --> 00:35:00.460
are most confident of
their ability to multitask

00:35:00.460 --> 00:35:03.460
are actually the worst at it.

00:35:03.460 --> 00:35:05.300
And why might that be?

00:35:05.300 --> 00:35:08.900
It might be that
they've lost the ability

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:12.230
to be mentally agile, because
they're just totally bombarded

00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:13.230
all the time.

00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:15.300
It's really interesting.

00:35:15.300 --> 00:35:16.930
And I think, also,
the trope that's

00:35:16.930 --> 00:35:18.638
been out there for a
long time that women

00:35:18.638 --> 00:35:22.360
can somehow multitask, right?

00:35:22.360 --> 00:35:24.930
For the women in the
audience, don't believe it.

00:35:24.930 --> 00:35:27.750
When it comes to the kind of
conscious work that we're doing

00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:29.580
at work, we really can't.

00:35:29.580 --> 00:35:31.010
We're no different from men.

00:35:31.010 --> 00:35:32.700
So just to lay
that one out there.

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:33.720
Yeah.

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:34.876
Thank you.

