day changed when you started
working at home and away

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:47.224
from other people with less
things to influence you

00:35:47.224 --> 00:35:48.640
and less things
to notice that you

00:35:48.640 --> 00:35:50.655
could frame in positive ways?

00:35:50.655 --> 00:35:52.780
CAROLINE WEBB: That's a
good, interesting question.

00:35:52.780 --> 00:35:56.770
I've had quite a few different
types of work and career

00:35:56.770 --> 00:35:57.270
in my life.

00:35:57.270 --> 00:36:02.120
And I definitely think that when
you move into a new setting,

00:36:02.120 --> 00:36:04.410
you don't have to take
a step back and say, OK,

00:36:04.410 --> 00:36:08.320
some of the things that I
did before-- it is different.

00:36:08.320 --> 00:36:11.910
The multitasking example
was so vivid to me.

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:13.510
I thought I really nailed this.

00:36:13.510 --> 00:36:15.250
And then, actually,
oh, my goodness.

00:36:15.250 --> 00:36:18.800
I really haven't because of
the change in circumstances.

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:21.900
So I guess what I would
advocate is just checking in

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:24.060
with yourself and
developing a self-awareness

00:36:24.060 --> 00:36:27.130
so that you maybe
take the principles.

00:36:27.130 --> 00:36:29.640
The stuff in the
book I've seen work

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:31.149
across lots of
different settings

00:36:31.149 --> 00:36:32.940
and lots of different
industries and roles.

00:36:32.940 --> 00:36:35.880
And the stories in
the book reflect that.

00:36:35.880 --> 00:36:39.160
So I've tried to
create a manual that

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:42.450
can sort of apply to all
sorts of different settings.

00:36:42.450 --> 00:36:44.819
But the way that it translates
into your own life, yeah,

00:36:44.819 --> 00:36:46.610
you need to experiment
with that, for sure,

00:36:46.610 --> 00:36:48.410
especially around
times of change.

00:36:48.410 --> 00:36:50.470
Yeah.

00:36:50.470 --> 00:36:52.180
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:52.980
This is fantastic.

00:36:52.980 --> 00:36:55.610
And I think it's--
certainly as, hopefully,

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:58.640
high-functioning adults, we
can take some of this to heart.

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:02.100
I'm wondering if you have any,
well, A, if there's research,

00:37:02.100 --> 00:37:04.660
or, B, if you have any
recommendations for how

00:37:04.660 --> 00:37:11.520
you would coach children
to implement some of this.

00:37:11.520 --> 00:37:15.990
CAROLINE WEBB: Well, I have
to say that most of my clients

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:17.430
have children.

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:21.290
And most of them tell me that
they practice on their children

00:37:21.290 --> 00:37:25.350
before they practice
on their colleagues.

00:37:25.350 --> 00:37:27.460
I hear a lot about
teenage children.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:29.470
I hear a lot about
spouses, actually.

00:37:29.470 --> 00:37:32.570
I've had a lot of people
tell me that the techniques

00:37:32.570 --> 00:37:35.310
have improved their marriage.

00:37:35.310 --> 00:37:38.620
I actually even had
one of my clients

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:40.887
tell me about how he had
used some of the techniques

00:37:40.887 --> 00:37:42.470
from the relationship
part of the book

00:37:42.470 --> 00:37:44.300
with his one-year-old son.

00:37:44.300 --> 00:37:48.300
So they were worried
that their son

00:37:48.300 --> 00:37:52.420
was slow in starting
to pick up language.

00:37:52.420 --> 00:37:56.960
And his wife was
particularly concerned

00:37:56.960 --> 00:38:01.130
that Francesca wasn't
speaking enough to the child.

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:05.550
And so Francesca, having fresh
from reading all the stuff

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:09.870
on relationships and rapport
and the power of actually truly,

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:12.450
deeply listening and
paying close attention

00:38:12.450 --> 00:38:14.240
and playing back
what you're hearing,

00:38:14.240 --> 00:38:17.820
decided to do that
with his young son.

00:38:17.820 --> 00:38:20.500
And so instead of
just talking at him,

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:23.840
he would listen so what
the little one was saying

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:28.780
and then repeat it back and then
add in one or two extra words.

00:38:28.780 --> 00:38:31.180
And his language
acquisition skills

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:33.240
went off the chart so quickly.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:35.647
Because even at
that young age, all

00:38:35.647 --> 00:38:38.230
of the things that we're talking
about in terms of competence,

00:38:38.230 --> 00:38:42.630
autonomy, security,
belonging, fairness respect,

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:45.130
these things kick in very early.

00:38:45.130 --> 00:38:51.190
So I would say that all of the
techniques, as far as I know,

00:38:51.190 --> 00:38:52.950
can be tried with children.

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:58.700
And I'd love to hear if
you'd like to give it a go.

00:38:58.700 --> 00:38:59.375
Thank you.

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:02.830
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:04.940
The tip that you gave
about using a timer

00:39:04.940 --> 00:39:06.330
sounds fascinating.

00:39:06.330 --> 00:39:08.340
I'm wondering if there's
an ideal amount of time

00:39:08.340 --> 00:39:09.580
that we can focus.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:10.413
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah.

00:39:10.413 --> 00:39:11.390
That's a good question.

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:14.620
There are lots of
different views on this.

00:39:14.620 --> 00:39:17.190
You've got people who swear by
the Pomodoro Technique, which

00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:19.299
is the 25 minutes.

00:39:19.299 --> 00:39:21.090
There are some people
who say 90 minutes is

00:39:21.090 --> 00:39:22.589
optimal for really deep work.

00:39:22.589 --> 00:39:24.880
I guess it goes back to the
earlier point-- you do need

00:39:24.880 --> 00:39:26.690
to experiment.

00:39:26.690 --> 00:39:27.610
I'll be honest.

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:31.270
When I came out
of corporate life,

00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:33.990
I had to start
with five minutes.

00:39:33.990 --> 00:39:36.360
I had to retrain myself.

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:38.150
And I started with five.

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:39.650
And then I went up to 10.

00:39:39.650 --> 00:39:42.000
And eventually, I
went around to 90.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:46.510
And then for me, I ended up
putting it back to 45 minutes.

00:39:46.510 --> 00:39:51.150
Because I found that I would
find it quite easy-- not easy.

00:39:51.150 --> 00:39:55.120
But I mean, it became second
nature to focus for 45 minutes.

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:56.780
If I was really
engaged in a task,

00:39:56.780 --> 00:39:58.390
then I'd go past the 45 minutes.

00:39:58.390 --> 00:39:59.790
And I'd feel really good.

00:39:59.790 --> 00:40:03.460
If I set it at 60
or 75 or 90 and then

00:40:03.460 --> 00:40:05.890
I kind of lost
focus before then,

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:08.490
it would set up a dynamic where
I'd be slightly disappointed

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:09.810
with myself.

00:40:09.810 --> 00:40:12.196
And I discovered it was
a much better dynamic

00:40:12.196 --> 00:40:13.820
to set it for a
shorter amount of time,

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:15.540
and I'd feel really
great about myself

00:40:15.540 --> 00:40:17.500
and then be more
inclined to try it again.

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.000
So I would start
small and build up.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:19.625
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:40:19.625 --> 00:40:21.620
So set really low
expectations for yourself.

00:40:21.620 --> 00:40:22.720
CAROLINE WEBB:
[LAUGHS] Yes, yes.

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:23.260
Yes.

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:24.740
I probably shouldn't admit
the five-minute thing.

00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:25.365
But I just did.

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:32.605
AUDIENCE: Do you have to
worry about realistic optimism

00:40:32.605 --> 00:40:36.510
or positivism
delaying change that

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:38.137
could help you in your life?

00:40:38.137 --> 00:40:38.970
CAROLINE WEBB: Yeah.

00:40:38.970 --> 00:40:41.520
Sometimes people say,
well, sometimes you just

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:43.540
need to quit your job, actually.

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:45.180
You're just not in
the right place.

00:40:45.180 --> 00:40:47.580
You're not in the right fit.

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:51.520
I think that sometimes you
do need to make big changes.

00:40:51.520 --> 00:40:54.630
And the one thing I
would say is that I

00:40:54.630 --> 00:40:57.010
think that focusing
on the day-to-day,

00:40:57.010 --> 00:41:01.100
focusing on improving the
small steps in your life

00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:04.360
puts you in a better position
to make the big decisions.

00:41:04.360 --> 00:41:06.300
If you're thinking about
making a career move,

00:41:06.300 --> 00:41:07.914
it's much more
likely that you'll

00:41:07.914 --> 00:41:09.580
make good choices if
you're not doing it

00:41:09.580 --> 00:41:11.360
from a place of desperation.

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:15.360
So the more that you can
improve the day-to-day, I think,

00:41:15.360 --> 00:41:18.760
the more that you'll, obviously,
enjoy the journey a bit more,

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:20.800
but you'll also probably
choose the destination

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:21.508
more effectively.

00:41:25.942 --> 00:41:28.150
ANANT SHUKLA: Do we have
any more audience questions?

00:41:32.390 --> 00:41:34.990
AUDIENCE: This is
actually just more

00:41:34.990 --> 00:41:37.790
of a comment about
the multitasking.

00:41:37.790 --> 00:41:40.020
My 86-year-old mother-in-law
claims that she can.

00:41:40.020 --> 00:41:41.480
And there's no
arguing that point.

00:41:41.480 --> 00:41:45.720
So where it became
really obvious to me

00:41:45.720 --> 00:41:48.670
about the automatic and
how when the automatic

00:41:48.670 --> 00:41:51.350
is no longer automatic-- it
really changes everything.

00:41:51.350 --> 00:41:54.040
I had a foot problem,
which was very painful

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:55.430
under the ball of my left foot.

00:41:55.430 --> 00:41:59.660
Every single step I took with my
left foot I had to think about.

00:41:59.660 --> 00:42:01.750
And if you don't think
your world doesn't

00:42:01.750 --> 00:42:04.172
change when you have
to think about walking,

00:42:04.172 --> 00:42:05.130
it's pretty incredible.

00:42:05.130 --> 00:42:07.800
And I would even
actually on the weekends

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:10.750
not do things because
the sheer energy

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:13.770
of having to walk to lower
Manhattan or do something

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:15.660
actually would
prevent me from doing

00:42:15.660 --> 00:42:18.340
that because of all the thinking
involved-- not the pain.

00:42:18.340 --> 00:42:19.730
I'm living with that.

00:42:19.730 --> 00:42:21.720
But it's the thinking
about the walking.

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:22.803
CAROLINE WEBB: Absolutely.

00:42:22.803 --> 00:42:23.950
Beautiful example.

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:26.500
Our brain's working memory
has such a small capacity

00:42:26.500 --> 00:42:31.180
that even a blinking light or a
buzzing phone or something that

00:42:31.180 --> 00:42:35.300
is as simple as walking can
take part of your brain's

00:42:35.300 --> 00:42:37.860
mental energy and make it hard
to think about anything else.

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:39.000
Really nice example.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:40.163
Thank you.

00:42:40.163 --> 00:42:42.270
Thank you.

00:42:42.270 --> 00:42:43.061
ANANT SHUKLA: Cool.

00:42:43.061 --> 00:42:45.740
Well, hopefully everybody's
got a few insights and tips now

00:42:45.740 --> 00:42:47.109
that they can take away.

00:42:47.109 --> 00:42:49.150
Let's give another round
of applause to Caroline.

00:42:49.150 --> 00:42:50.191
CAROLINE WEBB: Thank you.

